image_2:
This picture has a person (possibly a man) in a side profile wearing blue shorts and a light yellow or tan Tshirt and a tan baseball type cap on backwards.  This person is recreating a mural on the back wall which has a dark blue (or black) background.  There also appears to be two outlets in tan on either side of the mural.  The floor appears to have a tan drop cloth.  The mural appears to be an abstract galaxy with colors swirling in an offset eye shaped pattern.  The center of the "eye" is white with mauve encircling the white "eye" with four whirling rays giving the sense of motion on a background of egg yolk colored yellow.  Beyond the yellow, are slim patches of concentric colors of various blues, purples & a hot pink.  These areas surround the main "eye" giving the painting a feel of hurricane like movement.

In the forefront of the picture, I see almost a dark black shadow of a person but in their hand (which is clearly shown) is a red plastic cup of baby blue paint that appears to have been used in the painting and a used brush with the same blue paint appears beyond the shadow.  I assume it is being held by the shadow person.  Also it appears that the visible hand, behind the red cup, is holding a picture of what is to be recreated on the wall.  There is a strange sense of duality with the two pictures in the picture.  The wall mural doesn't seem to be an exact copy of the picture but the colors & movement seem a fairly good replication.  The small "original" picture seems to have more of an angular slant to it but the wall mural appears to be still in process and it may be more like the original in the final product.

Almost hidden at the bottom of the picture and behind the "original" picture is a worker sitting on their knees with the same clothing as the standing painter, but the head, shoulders are obliterated by the held picture.  I assume this is a woman due to the wider hips, but it may be a man.

image_1:
Many jobs offer break rooms for employees to take some time away from their desks and rejuvenate. The break rooms may contain tables for eating and TVs to watch during the off time. Many employees, however, wind up using these break rooms to discuss aspects of their jobs and work related activities, which makes it difficult for the employee to separate themselves from work.

In the picture above, we have employees congregating in a room with a television on in the background, but it seems the employees are more involved with discussion amongst themselves than taking time off. In fact, one woman (in the purple dress) carries a clipboard and is likely discusssing HR related topics with an employee. The two men behind them are discussing something entirely different, although they appear to be equals in similar roles.

The break room, assuming that's what the room we are looking at is,-- as we only have a view from the doorway and have a limited scope in our vision-- is being used for work activities and is counter-productive. Employees of companies are all too often afraid of taking actual time away from the job and place too great of an importance ont he job itself. Breaks from work and occasional time, in the long run, allow for greater productivity.

image_1: In  this picture Janessa (purple dress) is talking to Victoria, a member of her team. Janessa is a bit of an overacheiver and will do whats required to get the job done,  even if it means staying late or working weekends. Victoria, on the other hand, is a party girl. She does her assignments at work, but only enough to get the task complete. When working with others, she is the last one to pitch in to do additional tasks. After a work day, Victoria leaves the office quickly to join friends for a night out. This particular week, Janessa and Victoria were asigned to a team to pitch a new company sales strategy. While they collaborate well enough to come  up with an idea, Victoria does not want to stay late to continue to work on it, as she thinks it is fine as it is. Janessa stays 2 more hours at work to make sure the presentation is good. On the day of the presentation, Victoria is late and Janessa has to present their work alone. After the presentation, Janessa walks to her desk and sees Victoria coming in from what looks like a night out, as evidenced by a party wristband. Janessa is furios. Janessa confronts her about the missed presentation, and lets her know she is going to report her to the manager.
image_2: Amy's son Victor is in love with space and the planet system. In school, science is his favorite subject. At home, Victor likes to read about newly found planets, asteroids, and watch sci fi movies. Over the weekend,Victor visits his dad house who lives an hour away. While there, Amy decides she will surprise Victor and turn his bedroom into a planetary dream world. Amy wants to create a wall mural that looks like outer space but she is not a good artist. She searches craigslist and fine a group of artists who create murals for a low price. She gives them a picture of Victors favorite picture of outer space and ask if they could recreate it on the wall that would be behind his bed. image_1: Two women are speaking to each other in an office building after a conference call. One is a secretary and the other is an account manager. There are a few male co-workers discussing the conference in the background. The secretary handss the account manager a phone message from a call that came in while the woman was in the conference. The message was to return the call to a client who was part of the subject of the conference. This client and a few others are part of a large investment by a merging firm. This client in particular has an account worth hundreds of thousands of dollars. In the conference the account manager was meeting with the regional manager and other account managers about new high profile clients and their excessive demands. The team detailed how to meet these demands without neglecting other clients and duties. This client message surprised the accoutn manager, but she is confident that she will be able to accommodate this big client. She tells the secretary to gather all files pertaining to the client in another small conference room. After going over updates with the client, the account manager has satisfied the customer and allowed herself time for lunch as well. The conference seems to have helped her with managing clients, and she feels proud that she has successfully applied her knowledge.
image_2: Four young female artists paint a mural on a wall together at their college. One of them looks at the painting from a distance with a smaller copy in hand. She is making sure that their work matches the original. The students are using various paintbrushes and oil-based paint. They have been assigned the task by their art professor as a group assignment. Other groups of students in the class were assigned similar tasks with a different copy/subject to paint. This assignment is also a mid-term exam. The students are enjoying the project, even if their grades depend on it. These four girls have been assigned to paint a picture of an animated hurricane with multiple colors. Dark purple, aqua, light blue, hot pink, yellow, and white come together beautifully against a navy blue background on the wall. With the wall as a canvas, this idea has developed into a brilliant recreation. The students will be enjoying the fruits of their labor soon, as they are almost finished. Without a doubt, this art piece should land them a high and passing grade on the exam.

image_2: Where there once was a blank wall, now there is  color and life.  The walls of our local cancer hospital are being transformed by young artists from the American Cancer Society to aid patients and their families in feeling  more comfortable when entering the hospital. These artists are donating their time and their talents to bring these walls to life. Bright colors and  works of art tend to lessen  the anxiety and fear of patients on their way to doctors appointments or treatment. These artist are former patients, family member or friends who have the  common bond of cancer. In having this  common bond, they are willing to donate their time and their skills to pay it forward as a way of expressing their gratitude and hope. The ambitious project is expected to transform all the walls of the lower level of the hospital from a dimly lit corridor to a bright, dramatic landscape. You can see the artist working from a rendering of a hurricane. The colors represent the bands of the hurricane but white is the peaceful center. It is an amazing gift to the patients of this hospital who have to walk these halls. The American Cancer Society artists are dedicated to transforming the halls into an intrepretive moral that all can enjoy for many years to come.

image_1: Basically, there's four people standing around in a room. Everyone is wearing office attire and conversing like typical co-workers. In the very back there's a high-definition television that might be tuned into the news channel. In the immediate foreground, however, there's an African American holding a clipboard conversing with what appears to be a narcissistic white coworker female fixing her hair. They both appear to be bored in this apparently forced interaction between two co-workers in this obviously staged photograph. Most peculiar about this image, perhaps, is the caucasian male in the center wearing a pink t-shirt and khaki pants. He appears to be enjoying the conversation with his slightly off-screen coworker. What's peculiar about this, however, is that they've obviously been compensated enough to fake enjoying what I'm sure is a highly forced interaction between what would otherwise be two very unlikely associates. Other things of note in this photograph is that the African American lady is wearing a watch that absolutely does not go with her outfit, a ring on each finger, and has her hair parted to her left. The white female in the foreground is wearing the dumbest orange wristband you could possibly find for an office setting such as this. The African American female appears to be counting on her fingers, possibly counting the seconds it was taking the photographer to capture this bland and boring scenario on his potato quality camera.
image_2: This photograph is of a group of caucasian females painting what appears to be a swirling space mass onto a brick wall. This photograph is already immediately more interesting than the last, as there's something actually happening as opposed to nothing at all. The painting starts off darker at the edges and gradually gets brighter towards the center. This leads me to believe that what they are painting is a mass of gases orbiting a start in space. In the foreground, there's a female holding the finished reference picture that they are all copying down. Also in her hand is a cup that appears to have paint around where she would be drinking, which I think is absolutely disgusting and completely unsanitary. It's worth mentioning that according to the reference picture, the painting on the wall is far from finished and will indeed likely take a couple more hours at least. Also worth mentioning is that the female most properly framed in the photo is wearing her hat backwards, which indicates she has no idea how hats work since the brim is meant to keep the sun out of your eyes rather than off your hair. Everyone in this photo appears to be wearing similar clothing, which is white shirts with minimal graphics and black shorts. This group also laid a tarp on the ground next to the wall they're painting in an effort to keep paint off of their immediate surroundings.

image_1: It is the first day of Shannon's new job at the consulting firm. She was determined to make a good impression and show all of her coworkers how capable she is, but so far her confidence has been shaken. The office culture is insular and not particularly welcoming to newcomers, and Shannon is experiencing a great deal of discomfort and uncertainty. She feels awkward around her new coworkers, particularly Mike, the large and gregarious director of her department. Although Mike has been cordial, she can't shake the feeling that he seems not to afford the same respect to female employees as he does with men. All of her interactions with him have been short and strictly related to business, and yet his conversation about fantasy football with Dave is entering its fifth minute with no signs of slowing down. Furthermore, while she is trying very hard to convince herself that it's only a coincidence, Shannon can't help but notice she is the only nonwhite person on the floor, except for Robert, although he comes and goes since he is the building's custodian. While she is resolved to maintaining a positive outlook, she must admit to herself that this job isn't all she hoped it would be. Still, in a way it only strengthens her determination to prove to them that she belongs there and will not be silenced or set aside. She will earn their respect, whether they want to give it to her or not.
image_2: Julie is a high school science teacher in a rural community. Because the staff size at the school is small, some teachers have to teach multiple content sections. Julie has always loved art, and so she volunteered to teach an elective art course. Many of her students come from impoverished backgrounds, and most do not plan on attending college. As a result, many students only do the bare minimum to get by. Julie struggles to impress a love of learning on her students. Fortunately, the kids who have taken her art class are already fond of her personally and share many of her values. They are keen on helping Julie light the spark of curiosity in their fellow students. For their end of semester project, the class designed a mural to paint on one of the bare walls in the cafeteria. The design they ended up agreeing on is an artistic representation of the Milky Way galaxy. As the class works on the mural, many students stop to ask them what it is they're working on. Julie is proud of her students for taking the initiative to use their artistic creativity to foster scientific curiosity in their peers and in future generations that will use the cafeteria.

Beyond a flimsy open door, a group of well dressed workers stand conversing. Near the doorway, a woman in a black dress, wearing an orange wristband, toys with her hair behind her head as she speaks to another woman wearing a plum colored dress. The second woman listens while idly fiddling with the two lower fingers on her left hand. She cradles a clipboard against herself with her left forearm. Besides the plum dress, this woman wears a blue and white watch on her left wrist and her own orange wristband on her right wrist. Her skin is a light milano, and her expression is focused as she listens to the black dressed woman speak.

Further into the room, behind the two women, two professionally dressed men are also speaking to one another. Both wearing beige khakis with arms crossed, the first man, in a blue shirt, appears to be reacting to something said by the other man, who is wearing a light pink shirt. Behind both groups of people, a tan desk is barely discernable. A monitor is mounted on the back wall, and on the monitor is a professional appearing design, primarily blue with other colors splashed in.
image_2:
A person with long, light brown hair stands watching three men paint a beatiful design onto a brick wall. The watcher can only be identified by her hair as she stands to the right of the frame; only the back of her head and a distinctly feminine hand give a hint as to her appearance. That hand, her left, raised in front of her holds both a red cup, once filled with light blue paint, and a small picture which matches the design being created.

The picture, and the design, show what appears to be a galaxy in bright, fluent colors. No stars are depicted here though. The galaxy is represented by swaths of brilliant colors on a background of dark blue. The center of the celestial body is pale and tan, surrounded by a pale pink and then bright yellow swirling circle. Beyond those colors, the artists have added various shades of blue, pink, and purple, including the shade of blue which once filled the red cup, splashed about in a cyclical manner to represent the shape and motion of their design. The wall painting is almost complete and it matches the picture accurately.

The painters themselves, engrossed in their work, are all wearing black shorts and white shirts, and at least one is wearing a tan baseball cap backwards on her head. The other two painters are partially obscured by the upraised picture.

image_2: This picture depicts part of an effort within the community to create meaningful graffiti that aims to educate and inform viewers. Usually graffiti doesn't serve the purpose of promoting positive change in the community. Further, it certainly almost never seeks to educate people. This is not the case here. A high school in the community created an initiative that seeks to place well-known scientific phenomena in graffiti form on buildings around the town to enhance the town and to promote positive change. In this particular picture we see a lady holding a picture herself of the image of the Milky Way that is being painted in front of her. In front of her are two other individuals actively putting the finishing touches on the graffiti. Not only does the graffiti provide an educational purpose, it also gives these high school students an opportunity to pursue their artistic pursuits through a positive medium. This particular piece of graffiti is being painted onto a part of the new complex devoted to science research and hopes to encourage young passerby to become interested in the field by introducing them to a colorful, beautiful image of the Milky Way.

image_1: Office Mixers are the worst. Imagine yourself, a new hire in corporate America. You sit at your desk and dream of 6 o clock. But wait! You've forgotten that it's Tuesday, the day of the after-work voluntary seminar on somethingoranother. You sigh, resign yourself to at least an hour of unpaid serfdom, and make your way up to the meeting room. Upon entering, you are greeted by a gaggle of your coworkers, slightly frumpy and disgruntled just like you. You nod emphatically and clutch a binder to your chest as the four of you struggle to find something to discuss. A cloud of misery hangs over the room.
image_2:
Lisa and Mark live in Brooklyn. Lisa and Mark are artists. For their most recent project, they have been comissioned by a friend in Bed-Stuy to paint a cinderblock wall with a cartoon-style mural of some astral body. 

Friends gather as Lisa and Mark project the image on their blank canvas. The wall is first painted a matte Navy. Then slowly, majestically, the mural takes on a celestial aspect, like the milky way or a pastel egg being scrambled. Friends pitch in with solo cups of paint here and there, but really, it is Lisa and Mark's creation. They fall back, sipping their cups of beer and ocassionally paint by accient, watching art unfold in front of their eyes. 

The floor has been thoughtfully covered with drop cloth, as to avoid splashing it with paint. Lisa and Mark wear their signature matching white tshirts. The shirts are in themselves a canvas, the paint splatter a momento of the moment.

image_2: Now in this picture that I once saw at the museum, it gave a fantasy kind-of feel to it. It was quite eccentric since there were two people drawing the picture with one helper at the same time, only one person was doing it on a different kind of canvas. Because of the brick-walled background, it looked kind of messy; but still beautiful at the same time. That was my favorite part about the painting, that a picture can be painted on any surface; but still have the ability to look beautiful. Now to go into more detail about this depiction, the vibrant colors are going in a swirling motion; such as the milky way that contains our universe along with the life that contains it; I feel that's what gives this picture it's fantasy-feeling qualities. The background to this picture is dark blue, which I assume is the space that moves beyond. To other people, it might look like a hurricane warning sign; which shows how dangerous it's going to be. It can also look like a fallen crater that came crashing down to Earth, and got bits and pieces ripped off of it. Another example to describe this picture is; a model of the Earth's insides. The middle of the painting would be the core, the orange would be the crater; and the rest of the colors could describe the Earth's crust. From all of these examples, I hope you can depict a feeling and picture of what this beautiful painting is.

image_1: The office manager, the woman in the purple dress, was upset with the HR payroll clerk. She made a point to stop her on her way out of the weekly Friday morning meeting to discuss her concerns. She came armed with a clipboard full of errors from employee time cards. When the HR payroll clerk, the woman in the black dress, first heard her call her name, she flinched. She knew she had not been as careful as she should have been double checking her work last week due to rushing to get off work early for her son's soccer game. The office manager had spent the better half of the early morning getting chewed out by the CFO of the company regarding these errors that had happened in the payroll department under her watch. She understood that her subordinate had a seemingly good reason for needing to leave work early but this did not excuse not making sure the job was done properly before doing so. She was so angry that she could barely hide it and put all of her aggression into sqeezing the clipboard into her body. She was so upset that even though she knew it was a bad idea to confront her in front of other colleagues she could not stop herself. The payroll clerk felt horrible because to make matters worse she had a hangover from going out with girlfriends the night before, She had even forgotten to take off the orange bar brand from her wrist that she now wore as a badge of shame. She still held a note in her hand that the accounting department had given her as a warning for what was to come, she knew her boss would not be happy. She was right, her boss was lived. The office manager told her if she ever did it again, they would be be out of a job.
image_2: The woman whose head you can see is the roomate of the painter. She came home early from work today to see how the unpacking was going on in their new apartment. She had spent a year saving up her half of the deposit to be able to get this amazing loft in downtown New York City. She could not have been more surprised to find her eccentric roommate had not unpacked a thing. She had also taken it upon herself to put a huge abstract mural on their soon to be new living room wall. She was dumbstruck as to what she should do. She had no desire to have this odd looking vomit of a rainbow in her main living area. She picked up a cup that laid on the floor holding blue paint. It was everything that she could do not to throw the blue paint on the wall and over her possibly soon to be ex-roommates head. The painter had taken a week without pay off so that she could be the one responsible to decorate and unpack their new loft. She had been pushing her friend to help her make some choices about what styles and designs that she should would want. Her non artistic roommate had told her she did not have a artistic bone in her body and had no time to worry about that, since she needed to pull in many more hours to pay for her half of the new rent. The painter had spent her own money for all the supplies and decided to make a design decision and use her 10 years of art school training and add something bright and original to their new home. She was very saddened to hear her roommate's disdain for her piece of work. She decided to ignore her grumbling and contine to just keep painting.

image_2: If you have never seen this picture before, you are missing out. Imagine first how the entire sequence of events is about to gradually take place. Start by opening and placing layers of newspaper on the floor near the blank walls of your living room. Then pretend for a moment, that you slowly dip the entire length of your beard into a bucket of swirled paint. Most importantly, try to remember to keep the entire portion of your beard moving at all times to avoid making a streak across your neck. After one minute, walk to the center of a living room wall and position your beard in such a manner that it appers as if you are about to apply broad circular strokes with your newly acquired paint brush. Now just go for it. Simply begin  making small circles and gradually increasing in diameter. Once all the wet paint on your beard is transferred to the wall, return to bucket of swirled paint and repeat the same process again. As paint inside the bucket begin to diminish, you might be required to insert your face deeper into the bucket in order for your beard to touch the paint located near the bottom. At this point, it is best to pinch your nostrils with two fingers to avoid drawing up any residual paint through your nose. You can imagine how some might want to continue without stopping or taking any break. In this case, grab a ladder to help with painting larger circles that eventually reaches the ceiling height.

image_2:
THIS PICTURE LOOKS AS IF AN ARTISTS IS TRYING TO RECREATE [OR PAINT] THE LIKENESS OF THE PHOTOGRAPH, WHICH IS IN THE IN THE FOREGROUND.  THE CANVAS IS RATHER LARGE, I MIGHT ADD.  THE ARTIST IS USING "WATERCOLOR" PAINT.  tHE COLORS CONSIST OF YELLOW, LIGHT BLUE, PURPLE, AND INDIGO.  THE YELLOW, PURPLE AND AND LIGHT BLUE PAINT IS DRAWN IN CIRCULAR MOTION.  ANOTHER FEMALE IS STANDING IN THE FOREGROUND HOLDING A "RED" PLASTIC DRINKING  CUP. CONCURRENTLY, ANOTHER PERSON IS "KNEELING" ON THE FLOOR, DIRECTLY BEHIND THE PHOTOGRAPH.

IF I WERE TO DESCRIBE THE PAINTING, I WOULD DESCRIBE IT AS "ABSTRACT ART."  ABSTRCT ART IS SYMBOLIC.  IN THE REAL WORLD IT DOES NOT REPRESENT A "PERSON", A "PLACE", OR A "THING". BUT, RATHER THE WORK IS JUDGED ON IT'S COLOR, SHAPE, AND SIZE.  THE MERIT OF THE WORK MIGHT ALSO BE JUDGED ON THE "SIZE OF THE BRUSH STROKE",  THE DEPTH OF THE PAINTING, OR SIMILARLY, THE "SCALE" OF THE PAINTING.  ALL OF THESE VARIABLES CAN OCCUR IN MANY EXTREMES AND DISTORTIONS.  IN FACT, EACH PERSON CAN INTERPRET ABSTRACT ART ACCORDING TO HIS/HER SENSIBILITIES.  IN OTHER WORDS, IT CAN MEAN DIFFERENT THINGS TO DIFFERENT PEOPLE.  

fOR EXAMPLE, WHEN I LOOK AT THE PAINTING REPRESENTED IN THE PHOTOGRAPH, I SEE THE CIRCULAR MOTIONS TO REPRESENT A STRONG GUST OF WIND, PERHAPS A TORNADO, HURRICANE, OR CYCLONE.  ANOTHER VIEWER MIGHT HAVE A DIFFERENT INTERPRETATION.

This picture is somewhat confusing. In the foreground is the back of a persons head- all we can really see is hair, which is long and brown, and a hand, which looks feminine and is holding a red cup and a picture. The picture is an abstract design in yellow, white, purple, coral, magenta, and blue against a black background. It looks like a swirling galaxy of stars, but in a wide variety of colors.

However, they still seem to be working on it so there is hope of getting this right eventually.

image_1: There are four people engaged in a business meeting.  It is very hectic because it looks as if they are getting close to a deadline and have no idea where to even begin with their project.  The lady in the purple dress holding the clipboard is the team leader and she is talking to the woman in the black dress, asking her for ideas.  The woman in the black dress has some ideas written on a piece of scrap paper but she doesn't think they are very useful ideas.  She has been distracted because is is pregnant and has been tired lately.  The two men in the background have some ideas but they are both discussing it to see if they are on the same wavelength with their ideas.  They might have a good idea but will need to run it by the boss first before implementing it.  It does not appear to be going well because instead of just brainstorming everyone is just panicking about the deadline and are not coming up with reasonable ideas.  The TV is on in the background to give ideas for the project but no one is paying attention to it.  The door is open because the boss is about to come through the door to ask everyone how the project is going.  None of the people even realize that the boss is standing there because they are so wrapped up in thinking of project ideas.
image_2: The woman in the white cap and shorts that is painting is a recent college graduate that graduated from art school with a bachelor's degree.  She is out to prove to herself and her possible new boss that she can paint amazing murals for public buildings.  If she can impress her potential boss, then she will be given the job and will be able to start paying back her student loans.  The people crouching and painting near the bottom already work for the boss lady, and they don't have as much to prove but are still trying hard to do a good job.  The boss lady is somewhat disappointed in the mural so far- there are many things in the original picture that are different sizes and colors than the wall mural.  She decides that she will give her intern one more chance to fix this mural to make it look like the original picture, otherwise the intern does not get the job.  The intern feels that the picture is open to interpretation while the boss wants it to look exactly like the original picture.  The boss lady feels that the picture is a lot more complex than the simplified version that her employees and the intern are painting.  She knows that anyone who looks at the mural will like it, but she really wanted it to look like the original picture.  She figures that if it doesn't look like the original picture, why even use one at all?

image_1:
Through an open doorway in an office building, we see four office workers holding two different conversation. There appears to be another flat screen television or computer monitor turned sideways in the distance.  Both monitors are so far in the backiground that they are blurry.  No other distinguishing features can be easily seen in the room.

The two females in the photo are closest to the doorway.  One has her back towards the actual door and appears to be straightening the back of her hair with her right arm.  The arm is blurred even though most of the rest of the photo is clear, so it seems likely that the photo was shot while she was in mid-motion.  She is wearing a black dress and has medium length dark brown hair.  She is also wearing an orange watch or bracelet on the arm that is in motion.  It is hard to say which due to the blurring.  Since we can see her in profile and her head is turned away from the door, it is hard to tell what race she is, but Caucasian or Latino seem probable due to her skin tone and hair color.  The woman she is conversing with is facing the doorway.  She has a clipboard held to her body with her left arm and she appears to be counting off tasks on her fingers.  The bottom two fingers on her left hand are out stretched.  Her mouth is closed, so she seems to be listening to the female in the black dress.  The woman with the clipboard is a somewhat light-skinned African American with straight black hair that goes just beyond her shoulders.  She is wearing a dark magenta dress and a blue wrist watch.

Behind the women, two Caucasian men are also having a conversation with their arms folded and held against their chests.  The taller man is on the same side of the room as the woman in the black dress.  He also is mostly turned away from us, although we can see the profile of his face.  Both men are wearing khaki dress pants and the taller man is wearing a light pink dress shirt.  He has short dark brown hair. image_2:
In this photo, we are looking over the left shoulder of someone who is hodling a red plastic cup full of light blue paint and a photo or print-out of a piece of modern art.  Almost a quarter of the right side of the photo we are looking at is taken up by the person whose shoulder we are looking over.  The red cup is about one third of the way in from the left side of the photo we are looking at.  Based on the size of the cup, the dimensions of the print-out is about 8 inches wide by 6 inches tall.  It is hard to say whether the person holding the cup is male or female, although the hand looks slightly feminine.  The skin is light olive colored.  The person has straight, dark brown hair that just covers the left shoulder.  Only that shoulder, the left hand, and a third of the back of the head can be seen for this person.  He or she appears to be wearing a black shirt, although it is hard to say the color with certainity because of blurriness and the hair.

Based on the crispness of the detail, the camera was focused on the print-out in the person's hand.  The artwork on the print-out is being reproduced by two people on a much larger scale on the concrete block wall that the person holding the print-out and cup is looking at.  The wall is also slightly blurry.  The print-out is being held behind the red cup and it has a white border of about a half-inch.  The artwork in the print-out shows an artist's impression of a swirling galaxy painted on a dark blue background.  The color pallette is mostly purples and blues with orange highlights and a white or cream colored center and one large yellow area close to the middle.  The center of the galaxy is approximately the center of the print-out.  Due to its orientation in the print-out, the galaxy looks approximately like a egg with the smaller end touching the upper left corner of the print-out and the wider end touching the bottom right corner.  The artwork is very two dimensional with large areas of solid color and no gradiation of tone.  The style is most reminiscent of Impressionism.

The large reproduction of the artwork on the concrete wall is very close to being completed.  It covers the wall from top to bottom.  There is a beige drop cloth on the floor and two electrical outlets or small pipes on the wall being painted,  The two outlets are about five inches up from the floor and have small light colored squares with dark circles in the center of each.  There is about 6 feet in space between them.  The entire wall has been painted a dark blue to match the dark blue background of the artwork excpet for these two small squares.  There are outlines of the few incomplete sections of the artwork in the upper left quadrant of the wall that still need to be filled in.  Most of the rest of the galaxy has already been reproduced.  There is also something else that is light blue and two colors of beige on the floor of the room.  It is mostly hidden by the person whose shoulder we are looking over, so it is not possible to tell what this object is.  

Both people who are reproducing the artwork are wearing dark colored shorts and white t-shirts.  They both have light colored skin.  One person is kneeling on the floor.  We cannot see exactly what this person is doing because the photo of the original artwork is hiding all but the lower back, left arm, and part of the legs.  We also cannot see enough detail to determine the gender of either person painting.  The other person who is painting is standing up and is wearing a white baseball cap with the brim turned to the back.  He or she appears to have long blonde hair.  This person is wearing a light blue glove on his or her right hand and is holding a red cup of paint in the other hand.  The standing person is painting the light purple area just outside of the center of the galaxy.

The photo is taken from the point of view of someone standing outside of a room seemingly intended for business meetings. The open, sliding door is off center to the left by a noticeable fraction. Her left arm is more extended, her hand holding what appears to be a rolled-up piece of paper between her middle and index fingers. She is seemingly speaking to the other woman, also a brunette, whose complexion is darker. She is wearing a magenta dress and facing the camera, though her eyes are fixed on the brunette woman. The woman in the magenta dress sports a light blue wristwatch, holds a clipboard close to her chest with her left arm, and seems to be stretching or keeping count on her left ring and pinky fingers by touching them with her closed right hand, arm bent at the elbow and pressed against her hip. 
Behind the two women are two men, also engaged in conversation. This man, who is seemingly a few inches shorter than the man in the pink shirt, is wearing a light blue button-up shirt tucked into a darker pair of pleated khakis. Not much of the room itself is visible, but you can see what seems to be a monitor or television hanging fairly high on the wall.
image_2:
In this picture, a woman in a backwards khaki baseball cap stands in front of a brick wall on which she is painting a mural. She is wearing tennis shoes, athletic shorts and a t-shirt, the backwards cap hiding only a portion of the blonde pony tail that extends between her shoulder blades. She stands straight-legged, leaning to the left slightly as her right hand, covered in light blue paint, continues to work on the artwork, which looks like a slightly abstract recreation of the Milky Way galaxy, rendered on a dark navy background with purples, varying shades of light blue, pink, yellow, and white. 
In the foreground of the picture, a woman stands with her back to the camera, her head and shoulders occupying only the right third of the frame, and slightly out of focus. Her raised left hand clutches a red plastic cup with light blue paint coated on the inside and splashed slightly beneath its lip, alongside three similar yellow splashes. 
She holds a paper copy of the mural seemingly between her fingers and the cup, which obstructs the bottom left part of what looks to be the finished design. The design on the paper looks like what's being painted on the wall, only with more splashes of the same colors.
There are two other painters working on the project, but the paper copy of the design obstructs most of them from the shot. They are both kneeling and seem to be working on the bottom part of the mural, both wearing white t-shirts.

image_1: A woman is pregnant with her first child.  Now that she is somewhat into her pregnancy, she decided with her husband to go to the OB/GYN to have a check up.  In this picture, you see the woman in black speaking to the Doctor, in purple.  The doctor is telling the patient about the baby's health and other statistics about it.  Behind the woman is her husband, who is talking to the OB/GYN assistant, who is also answering questions that he has about the baby.  As this is the couple's first child, they want to make sure they are prepared for knowing all they can about the pregnancy.  The doctor is also telling the woman about all the different stages of pregnancy and the milestones that her and her husband can expect as the pregnancy proceeds further.  The doctor tells the woman that the baby is very healthy and during the next check-up, which she has scheduled a couple of weeks later, she'll be able to use ultrasound to determine the baby's gender.  Both the woman and her husband are very excited and they can't wait to find out whether their new baby will be a boy or a girl.  The doctor also tells the woman additional do's and dont's to make sure their baby will stay healthy throughout the pregnancy.
image_2: Cindy is an aspiring artist.  For her whole life she always loved painting different murals and doing different arts project.  After graduating from college with a major in Art, Cindy had a tough time finding jobs to do.  Depending on the major you go with in college, there are either lots of jobs available after graduation, or very few.  Luckily for Cindy, after doing some samples of her Art, she was found by a local talent scout, Brad.  Brad was very impressed by Cindy's paintings and referred her to a client, Debbie, who needed a galaxy mural done for her brand new office.  After Debbie saw Cindy's work she chose her to do the mural for her office.  Seeing the size of the wall, Cindy knew she was going to have trouble doing it all alone, so she chose her fellow Art major friend, Samantha, to help her out doing the mural.  In this picture you can see Cindy painting the galaxy mural and finishing up it's final touches.  Below Cindy, you see her friend Samantha helping out with the galaxy.  Holding the little sample painting of the galaxy is Debbie as she watches both Cindy and Samantha putting the final touches on the galaxy mural in the office.

image_1: There are four people standing in an office setting together. There are two men standing in the background facing one another deep in conversation. There is a woman in a magenta dress holding a clipboard and gesturing to her middle finger with the alternate hand as if to indicate she is in the middle of a lengthy list of negative feedback for the younger woman in the black dress-whose face we cannot see.  The body language of the subordinate would indicate she is highly uncomfortable to receive any sort of criticism in public. She runs her hands through her shoulder-length brown hair nervously as she leans up against the door frame. She feebly tries to explain herself to her manager but the strained look on the supervisors face would indicate a bit of frustration with the performance of this worker.

image_1: The employees we waiting for the meeting to begin.  John and Bill were chatting about last weekend's football victory.  They were very excited their team appeared to be headed to the playoffs.  They discussed the fact that if the team won this weekend, the remainder of their schedule was pretty easy and the team should be able to beat all remaining teams played.  This would send the team to the playoffs for the first time in ten years.  Kim and Sarah we discussing the meeting they were waiting to attend.  Kim was worried about what the meeting could be about since no subject matter was discussed when the meeting was announced and attendance was mandatory.  Sarah listened intently as Kim guessed at possible topics.  Kim was worried that perhaps the company was downsizing.  She knew the company had been having financial struggles and that profit wasn't as large as previously projected.  She believed there were many employees who were not busy.  She was sure the company would see layoffs as a viable cost saving measure. She hoped that she was a valuable enough employee not to be impacted if her suspicions were correct.  As Sarah listened, she became increasingly agitated and prayed to herself that Kim was over-reacting.  She thought the meeting was probably about something far less negative.
image_2: Jan, Amy and Heather are students at the local art school.  The local news station, KESW, had contracted with the school to have a group of students paint a weather map on one of the station's outside walls.  The station provided a photo of the map they wanted to be painted,  The school decided that the three girls were well suited for the task.  They arrived at the studio and sketched the outline of the map on the wall. They decided to take turns painting in colors they had chosen.  Each girl was responsible for 2-3 colors.  When Jan had finished the larger portions of the light blue color she had chosen, she waited as Amy and Heather painted their sections. She studied the photo and figured out the smaller portions she still needed to paint blue.  She was very  happy with the progression of the project because replicating the photo was a success!  She knew that doing such a good job on this assignment would lead to other assignments during the time she had left before graduating.  She hoped that she would be able to work which Amy and Heather again. She felt they had worked very well together and she really liked both of them.  They had already discussed their plan to go to the local sports bar after completing the painting to celebrate their success with beer and a burger.

image_2: First, before we embark on this vast journey of explanations, please remember that mass is the amount of matter, or "stuff", in an object. Thank you. Okay, as you imagine in your mind, picture a black hole as a place in space where gravity pulls so much that even light are unable to escape or get out. That's right. Try to visualize how this gravity can be so powerful, such that even matter has been squeezed into a tiny space. This usually can occur when a star is in the process of dying. So because no light can get out, us humans technically cannot see black holes. If you think about it, they are actually invisible. Only certain space telescopes with specailized tools can help find black holes. These specialized toos can observe how stars that are very close to black holes act differently than other stars. Now black holes can be big or small. Scientists think the smallest black holes are as small as just one single atom. These black holes are very tiny but have the mass similar to that of Mount Everest. As we head towards the opposite end of the size spectrum, there is a kind of black hole called "stellar". Its mass can be up to 20 times more than the mass of our sun. As matter of fact, there may be numerous stellar mass balck holes currently in our Earth's galaxy. However, the largest black holes are called "supermassive". These black holes have masses that are more than 1 million suns together. Scientists have provided us with proof that every large galaxy containes a supermassive black hole at its center. How cool is that?

image_1: This eems like a professional conversation between both women in the picture, the darker-skinned woman being the superior and the lighter skinned woman is her assitant or intern. The intern is recieving or reporting on a task she was given and is now having trouble at with some aspect of it. She is asking her supervisor for her assitance or suggestion on what she should do next. The task itself is relatively important for the company because it shows the statistics of the past 2 years and having that knowledge will defintely help the results for the following year by determining strengths and weaknesses of the company's sale staff. Because of her unfavorable work ethic, the assitant is getting more and more frustrated about the task at hand and is beinging to worry that she may be fired. Her supervisor, although knowledgable about her past mistakes is willing to give the girl one final chance to turn things around. She is thinking, "This may be her last chance to get where she wants to be in life and this may be the time she starts getting her life together." The dark skinned supervisor is very understanding and forgiving, sometimes more than she should be.
image_2: This is the work of a very talented graffitti artist. The artist uses different bold colors to offer a general visual contrast within the piece but also arranges his colors specifically enough to where all the colors flow together really well to create a stunning visually compelling piece of illegal or comissioned street art. This piece is of a galaxy, possibly the galaxy in which we all exist. He or she is working from 'back to front', which is a method to approach painting more complex images where the artist starts by layering simpler colors that will eventually lead up to more complex colors, shapes and textures. the base layer, as it is usually called, generally just serves as a basic guideline for whatever image you are creating. It helps by giving the artist an idea of what the painting looks like before investing too much time into something being wrong. This method allows for mistakes to be corrected early in the painting process so that more efforts wont be made to correct mistakes that would have been made in the future, possibly delaying the finished product if not ruining it altogether. It seems like the artist is working on the base layer in this picture while having another artist, possibly a friend, to help with the proportions of the image being transferred onto the wall. Although the image itself is not too complex these methods are actually very important in any painting process and should be used by anyone that attempts to have a job in this profession.

image_1: A doorway is filled with co-workers discussing a very important project. Janet, the project lead is wearing a pink dress and is talking to Nancy, who is the lead developer for the development team and is wearing a black dress. Joe the lead engineer  is wearing his usual long sleeve shirt and talking to Darren the web developer. Since the next release of the company web portal is coming up next week they are meeting one last time to finalize the documentation and sign off on a few other matters. The team based in New York has traveled to HQ in Phoenix and the time has come to decide what to do for dinner this evening. Janet wants to keep it simple and order wraps and salads for the whole crew but Nancy thinks the group should celebrate by heading over to the local pub for happy hour. Nancy says, "So what does everyone want to eat? I say we go to a pub...". Joe replies, "I am all for that, what do you say, Darren?". To which Darren nods in agreement. Janet smiles and nods, and says, "You read my mind". So the group heads down to the pub which is located conveniently downstairs. There is a dj playing and the group is in very high spirits. Janet orders a glass of wine for herself and offers to buy Nancy a drink to which she says, "Yes, thanks!, I'll get the next round". Joe mentions to Darren that he has the hots for Nancy even though she is married. Darren says, "I'd hit it". Joe says, "You dog you". Janet turns around and whisper's, "I heard that and smiles". Joe says, "I'd hit that too".

image_1: This is a picture of Karen.  She is working on a very important project at work, but has had some seeds of doubt in the back of her mind. image_1: At 4:00 p.m. on Friday, September 25th the supervisor called a meeting. As the employees were gathering in the room waiting for the supervisor to arrive the conversation drifted to what the meeting could be about. There had been rumors for weeks about possible layoffs. There had also been rumors of possible promotions. Nobody knew what would come next. There was nervous laughter, that fake kind of laughter where you're pretending that everything is okay, but deep down inside you know something is wrong. Sheryl, in the purple dress, had worked at the company for 5 years now and had been promoted twice. She hoped that this would be the third time, but the rumors of layoffs shaded her optimism. The company's stock price had taken a hit that week, something was a amiss in the labrynth of paperwork that was being explored by the Federal Trade Commision. Tax shelters or phony earnings reporting. Something like that. Nothing that would ever effect her personally if it hadn't effected the entire company and put it at risk for bankruptcy. So now she awaits her fate, hoping she doesn't have to walk in the door tonight and put on a brave face for her daughter while knowing she has to find a new way to provide for her. Back to public school perhaps. Maybe downsize to a smaller house. Or take out a second mortgage until she could find a new job. The meeting was called. And all the boss said was that the Christmas party would be at the downtown Marriot this year and gifts were optional.
image_2: This how a starving artist begins her life. On a wall at a high school. Angie had put together the concept on a computer wondering how Da Vinci would marvel at such a tool. Now it seemed so easy to create. But was that a good thing or was the barrier to entry to the art world too low now? If everyone has the tools to create, if those tools have made art easier to create then how is greatness recognized? It was a dumb project anyway. Her art teacher, Ms. Lawson, has asked for volunteers, and after about twenty seconds of excurciating silence she had raised her hand. For the past few weeks she had been working with virtual paints to smear them together into a cohesive whole. The subject was diversity. She had been asked to interpret this however she wanted. She chose a galaxy, because what's more diverse, what's more inclusive than a million billion light years of stars or however big it was. She didn't know. Hey, she's not going to major in science. She's majoring in Art. With a capital A. Angie is going to be a serious Artist and this, in her mind, is her first big break. So now here she stands in front of the watchful eye of Ms. Lawson--who Angie believes to be severely bitter over her own failure to become an Artist with a capital A--here she stands, with her brush and her mind and her first giant step toward being and Artist.

image_2: Mackenzie has always been fascinated with weather and natural disasters. Since she was a young child her mother bought her countless books about tornadoes, hurricanes, volcanoes, among others. She dreamt of becoming a meteorologist when she grew up. Even as young as the age of six she could see herself on television, but not as a pop star or singer, as a meteorologist! As she grew older her love for storms and natural disasters only grew. She checked the weather every morning before school to see what kind of day she would be witnessing. Anytime that her family would travel she would keep them informed with what kind of outdoor conditions they would likely encounter along the way. Although she was truly passionate about the weather, she naturally picked up other talents as well. She loved to paint and play the violin. While in college she got the opportunity to paint a mural of a hurricane for her school. She was truly in love with the idea of merging two of her passions together. So as her friends helped her with setting up the paints and providing the picture they would use they got to work. Now here they are nearly finished painting a picture of the hurricane that came through and caused so much wreckage in the city just two short years earlier. Here the community will be able to witness her talent where she put more than just paint on the wall, she also put her passion for the storm. The painting sparks rememberence in many that witnessed or heard of the hurricane. The painting for many remind them of the helpfulness of the members of the community. True caring and compassion swept through the city as everyone helped to rebuild not only the city but the people in it as well.

They don't particularly care for one another, but they do have a healthy amount of respect for one another and they take each other's ideas seriously. After bouncing ideas off of one another, one employee asks the other if she'd like to sit down over lunch and discuss it further. The other agrees. They both leave this conversation a bit skeptical but assured that they will be able to get their jobs done in a good and efficient manner. There is no wonder as to whether the job will be completed. And, as tense as the conversation was, they both feel a bit more relaxed, now. It's out of the way, and the future looks to be a bit easier.
image_2: This picture represents, in its own way, everything that has ever been. One could look at the photo or mural and see that this is how the cosmos has been operating since the dawn of time. Is the center of the mural a black hole, and is that the milky way spinning around the center of it? Or is the center a random star with planets and space debris revolving around it? But, the thing is is that this photo doesn't even have to represent the larger scale. There are, in fact, structures right in the human brain that look like this; a central neuron with neural pathways spinning off of it and traveling in different directions. This pattern also represents water in a few different ways: water running down a drain, water spinning into a whirlpool, and even water in a bath after it's been brushed by a hand. It could also be an idea. As we all know, ideas have a core as their center and then a bunch of other smaller ideas that spin off of it. What's happening in this picture is everything that has ever happened. Or, perhaps it's just a bunch of nothing with a central core.

image_1: A few office workers are standing around talking to each other in an office.  Four people are visible; two women stand in the foreground, in a doorway, talking to each other.  In the background, beyond the doorway, two men are talking to each other as well.  Beyond them we can glimpse a computer screen or two.  The men's body language (relaxed posture, arms folded loosely, relaxed faces) indicates that they are having a casual conversation, but the women appear to be having a more serious discussion.  The face of the woman on the right is clearly visible; she looks severe, perhaps mildly unhappy.  She is carrying a clipboard, giving her an air of authority.  The woman on the left has her back to the photographer, but the way she is leaning back from the other woman, almost as if backing through the doorway, and running her hand over her hair, indicates she is in some distress.  The woman on the right is black and wearing a purple dress.  The woman on the left is white and wearing a black shirt and black slacks.  Both men in the background are white and wearing light-colored button-down shirts and light-colored slacks.
image_2: A woman observes three people who are painting a mural on a wall.  The picture is taken so we see little of the woman - just a part of the back of her head and shoulder.  In front of her, she holds a picture that appears to be the same picture now being painted on the wall, and the proximity of the picture in her hand to the wall mural indicates that she is comparing the two.  Because of the way she is holding up the picture, we can only see one of the three painters clearly; the other two are largely blocked from the camera lens.  In the same hand that she holds the picture, the woman holds a red plastic cup that appears to contain light-blue paint of the same color being used in parts of the mural.  This suggests that she is one of the artists involved in the work.  The artists appear to have sketched the outlines of the painting (which is rather abstract, purple, yellow, pink, and multiple shades of blue color swirling around a white center, in a shape reminiscent of a galaxy) on the wall, and are now filling in the spaces with the correct colors, using the picture as a guide.  All three artists currently in front of the painting wear white t-shirts and black shorts with sneakers; the one artist who is fully visible has a baseball cap on her head.

There is a thin, business sized slip of paper between her middle and index finger. A metallic watch is around her left wrist. image_2: The girl in the backwards cap is in high school and she has been given permission from school administrators to paint a mural on a wall in the cafeteria along with other members of the student group S.A.A.D., or Students Against Drunk Driving. The school administration hoped giving these S.A.A.D. students the opportunity to paint a mural would give exposure to the important work they do within the school community. For their part, the girl in the backwards cap and her fellow S.A.A.D. members spent much time figuring out a plan for their mural. They utilized many resources in the school's arts department and asked a well-known artistic student in the school if they could model their mural after some of his artwork. He created an original piece using the computer program Photoshop. The premise behind his creation came from meshing images of the human brain after copious amounts of alcohol have been consumed with colors of various alcoholic beverages. The girl in the backwards cap and the other S.A.A.D. students were very happy with the outcome. They felt it had a futuristic feel and really added to the school cafeteria. Most importantly, they thought it would be a great story to tell when they revealed the piece to school administrators and the student body as a whole.

image_1: Mulan is a mid-level engineer at a progressive company that makes components used in Formula One race cars. Mulan has been at the company for only a few months and her job currently related to an upcoming Formula One race event. In addition to her regular responsibilities, Mulan likes to review data on key pieces of equipment. Mulan has a reputation in the industry for raising concerns about issues that other people either do not notice, or do not find problematic. While reviewing records this week, Mulan noticed what seemed to be failures in one of the component parts that connect to her equipment. While viewing a large set of schematics from recent track tests showing heat-related failures and graphs of temperature data, Mulan observed some burn patterns showing that, on a couple of the laps, a failure had apparently occurred that could have created an engine fire, though fortunately this did not happen. She became convinced that the design of athis part is fatally flawed and must be changed. However, this is something that could take months and cost beyond hundreds in thousands of dollars. In addition, rejecting the current design could delay scheduled track tests.
image_2: Joann had always wanted to paint exactly what was on her mind. But when she asked her friend to comment on her recent art rendition of the Milky Way at a nearby homeless shelter, she told her that more work on it would be necessary. For the next few days, Joann started feeling terribly sick and was unsure what the cause was. Symptoms of Joann's illness included: hair lice, paint intoxication, latex allergies, athlete's foot, breast-nipple rash, loss of appetite, shortness of breath with movement, sweating, and occassional vaginal yeast infectoin. By the end of the week, Joann finally decides to contact Doctor Victor Mott's office where the receptionist managed to find a rush sick appointment that afternoon. As a starving street artist, Joann does not get sick often but also does not have health coverage that permits seeing any of the doctors praticing in the local physician's clinic. So after checking in at the front desk, nurse Flanders acknowledged Joann's dilema and offered her a possible alternative. At this point, Joann wished this scenario was all but a nightmare which she can quickly wake up from. Nurse Flanders then asked Joann to follow her into a dimly-lit room. Alone and a tad nervous, Joann was instructed to view the first 10 minutes of the 1992 film, The Hand That Rocks the Cradle. When the video clip was over, there was some faint tapping on the door, and in comes a man who gently  introduced himself as simply "Dr. Mott of the Milky Way Pipeline Once Bitten Twice Shy".
